    <thetext>(In reply to comment #0)
&gt; The API tooling detects a problem in
&gt; org.eclipse.mylyn.htmltext.ui/src/org/eclipse/mylyn/htmltext/configuration/AutoparagrahConfiguration.java:
&gt; AutoparagrahConfiguration extends non-API type ConfigurationElement. This
&gt; should be fixed or filtered with a comment.

Steffen, could you give me a hint how to resolve this warning?

I guess it is bad practise to have a super-class in an internal package which is extended by API classes because all public and protected methods will become API.

What is the best way to remove this warning?
* Making the super class API? (in this special case moving the super-class into another non-internal package)
* Adding a usage-problem filter (what does it mean if the project has usage-problems?)</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
    <commentid>2076563</commentid>
    <comment_count>4</comment_count>
    <who name="Steffen Pingel">steffen.pingel</who>
    <bug_when>2012-03-07 09:17:59 -0500</bug_when>
    <thetext>Moving the super class into an API package would be the best solution. If needed you can annotate methods with @noreference to disallow access but in general I would try to avoid that and use private/package access to control access.

Usage filters will basically suppress warnings but the problems will still be there. I sometimes use them if we intentionally use classes in an unintended way. While much quicker fixing the problems is definitely the better solution :).</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
